<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="143" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1444,992,1739]" pageId="1" pageNumber="143">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1604,1630]" pageId="1" pageNumber="143">Etymology</emphasis>
. The new species name is derived from the Latin word “ 
<emphasis box="[957,1095,1604,1630]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="143">longiradiate</emphasis>
”, referring to the aedeagal has a elongate forked processes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="143" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1444,992,1739]" pageId="1" pageNumber="143">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1676,1702]" pageId="1" pageNumber="143">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Matsumura" baseAuthorityYear="1914" box="[618,785,1677,1702]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Bhatia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="satsumensis">
<emphasis box="[618,785,1677,1702]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="143">B. satsumensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but can be distinguished from the latter by the aedeagus shaft without processes and with the shaft short and triangular in dorsal view.
</paragraph>
